\begin_layout Problem
Given a resonator with one plane mirror (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}=\infty$
\end_inset

) and one curved mirror (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}=4$
\end_inset

m), with a separation of 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1$
\end_inset

m, is it stable?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
g_{1} & = & 1-\frac{L}{R_{1}}=1-0=1\\
g_{2} & = & 1-\frac{L}{R_{2}}=1-\frac{1}{4}=\frac{3}{4}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\leq g_{1}g_{2}=1(\frac{3}{4})=\frac{3}{4}\leq1
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq g_{1}g_{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

, the resonator is stable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Write the matrix for one complete round trip of a ray in a cavity consisting
 of a plane mirror (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}=\infty$
\end_inset

) and an 
\begin_inset Formula $R=3$
\end_inset

m mirror separated by 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1$
\end_inset

m.
